When looking at these results it is clear that this data is unbalanced severely.
Although a majority-class classifier achieves an accuracy of approximately 91.9%, this performance is misleading. Such a model would never predict a default and therefore would fail to identify any high-risk borrowers.

In the context of credit risk modeling, the minority class—defaults—is of primary interest because misclassifying a defaulting customer as low risk can result in substantial financial losses. Accuracy treats all classification errors equally and is therefore dominated by the majority class in highly imbalanced datasets.

As a result, accuracy alone is not an appropriate evaluation metric for this problem. More informative metrics that focus on the model’s ability to identify defaults, such as recall, precision, AUC, or cost-sensitive measures, will be necessary in later stages of the project.

