  )

head(missing_compare)

```

The application datasets contain substantial missing data across many variables. While a large number of features are fully observed, several variables exhibit moderate to high levels of missingness, reflecting differences in data availability across external data sources rather than random data loss.

Removing rows with missing values would result in a significant reduction in sample size and is therefore not appropriate. Instead, a combination of column filtering and imputation is more suitable. Variables with extremely high missingness may be excluded from modeling, while numeric variables can be imputed using median values and categorical variables can be imputed with an explicit “Missing” category.

Additionally, missingness itself may be informative for credit risk assessment. For selected predictors, missingness indicators will be created to allow models to capture this information. This strategy balances information retention with model robustness and will be applied consistently to both training and test datasets.

