Several data quality issues were identified during exploratory analysis. Some time-based variables use non-intuitive encodings; for example, DAYS_BIRTH is recorded as a negative value representing days prior to application and should be transformed into age in years for interpretability. Additionally, DAYS_EMPLOYED contains a large placeholder value that indicates applicants who are not currently employed. This value does not represent a real duration and should be treated as missing, potentially with an accompanying employment indicator variable.

Monetary variables such as income and credit amount exhibit strong right skew and extreme values. These appear to be legitimate outliers rather than data entry errors and should be retained, though transformations may be beneficial for certain models.

Finally, some variables display zero or near-zero variance, indicating limited or no informational value. Such variables are unlikely to contribute meaningfully to predictive performance and can be removed during preprocessing.

Transformations Needed for Modeling (Initial Thoughts)

The application data will require transformation prior to modeling, although the specific preprocessing steps will depend on the modeling approach. Linear and regularized models require numeric predictors to be on comparable scales, categorical variables to be encoded, and missing values to be imputed. In contrast, tree-based models are more robust to skewed distributions and do not require feature scaling, though they still require consistent handling of missing values and categorical encodings.

Exploratory analysis has already identified several variables that would benefit from transformation for interpretability, such as converting DAYS_BIRTH into age in years and addressing placeholder values in DAYS_EMPLOYED. Monetary variables exhibit strong skew and may benefit from log transformations for certain model types. These considerations will guide preprocessing decisions in later stages of the project.
