Transactional data from previous loan applications was aggregated to the applicant level and joined to the application dataset. This aggregation preserved the one-row-per-applicant structure required for modeling.

Several aggregated features show meaningful relationships with default status. Applicants with a lower historical approval rate and different patterns in the number of previous applications tend to exhibit higher default rates. These findings suggest that historical credit behavior captured in transactional datasets provides additional predictive signal beyond the application-level features alone.

Missing values introduced by the join primarily reflect applicants with no prior credit history, which is itself potentially informative and should be handled carefully during modeling.